Here's a Java solution using bit manipulation without loops or recursion. The property for a number being a power of three based on its binary representation is that the exponent of the first '1' starting from right and counting towards left should be a multiple of 3 minus one (i.e., 0, 1, or 2):

```java
public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
    int pow = 1; // Initialize base as 1
    while (n > 0 && (pow << 1) <= n) { // While n is greater than zero and next power of two is less than or equal to n
        pow *= 3; // Multiply by 3
        int binaryDigitPosition = Integer.numberOfLeadingZeros(n); // Get position of leading zeros in binary representation
        if ((binaryDigitPosition & 3)!= 0) { // Check if the position has remainder other than 0 when divided by 3
            return false;
        } else {
            n -= pow; // Subtract current power of 3 from n
        }
    }
    return n == 1; // Return true if we have reached base case (n becomes 1 after removing all powers of 3)
}
```

This function uses `Integer.numberOfLeadingZeros()` method which calculates the number of leading zeros in the given binary representation. This approach checks whether each digit contributes to the power of three or not and continues this process until reaching the base case (when only one power of three remains).

